# TypeScript Advanced Types

Advanced types are where TypeScript becomes a **type-level programming language**. You can write logic — conditionals, loops (mapped types), string manipulation (template literals) — but all of it runs at compile time on types, producing zero JavaScript output.

## Conditional Types

The mental model: a ternary expression for types.

```
T extends U ? TrueType : FalseType

'Is T assignable to U?'
Yes → resolve to TrueType
No  → resolve to FalseType

Example trace:
  type IsString<T> = T extends string ? 'yes' : 'no';
  IsString<string>   → 'yes'
  IsString<number>   → 'no'
  IsString<'hello'>  → 'yes'  (string literal extends string)
```

```ts
// Basic conditional type
type IsArray<T> = T extends any[] ? true : false;
type A = IsArray<number[]>;  // true
type B = IsArray<string>;    // false

// Conditional + union distribution
// When T is a union, conditional types DISTRIBUTE over each member:
type OnlyStrings<T> = T extends string ? T : never;
type C = OnlyStrings<string | number | boolean>;
// = OnlyStrings<string> | OnlyStrings<number> | OnlyStrings<boolean>
// = string             | never                | never
// = string
```

```
Distribution visual:

OnlyStrings<string | number | boolean>
  ↓ distributes over each union member
  string extends string  → string
  number extends string  → never
  boolean extends string → never
  ↓ union of results
  string | never | never = string
```

## The `infer` Keyword — Pattern Matching on Types

`infer` lets you **capture** a portion of a type and give it a name inside a conditional branch.

```ts
// Extract the element type from an array:
type ElementType<T> = T extends (infer U)[] ? U : never;
type N = ElementType<number[]>;   // number
type S = ElementType<string[]>;   // string
type X = ElementType<boolean>;    // never (not an array)

// Extract return type of a function:
type ReturnOf<T> = T extends (...args: any[]) => infer R ? R : never;
type R1 = ReturnOf<() => string>;       // string
type R2 = ReturnOf<(x: number) => boolean>; // boolean

// Infer a Promise's resolved value:
type UnwrapPromise<T> = T extends Promise<infer V> ? V : T;
type V1 = UnwrapPromise<Promise<number>>; // number
type V2 = UnwrapPromise<string>;          // string (not a promise, returns as-is)
```

```
infer mental model — pattern match at type level:

  T extends (infer U)[]      ← pattern: 'T must be an array of SOMETHING'
                    ▲
                'capture whatever SOMETHING is into U'

  If T = number[]
    T matches (infer U)[] with U = number  → resolves to number

  If T = boolean
    T does NOT match (infer U)[]            → resolves to never
```

## Mapped Types — Transform Every Property

Mapped types iterate over the keys of a type and produce a new type:

```ts
// Template: { [K in keyof T]: NewType }

// Make all properties optional (Partial<T> is implemented this way):
type MyPartial<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };

// Make all properties readonly:
type MyReadonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };

// Transform values — wrap every property in a Promise:
type Async<T> = { [K in keyof T]: Promise<T[K]> };
type AsyncUser = Async<{ name: string; age: number }>;
// { name: Promise<string>; age: Promise<number> }

// Add a prefix to all keys using template literal types:
type Getters<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as `get${Capitalize<string & K>}`]: () => T[K]
};
type UserGetters = Getters<{ name: string; age: number }>;
// { getName: () => string; getAge: () => number }
```

```
Mapped type iteration:

  { [K in keyof User]: ... }

  K iterates over:  'name' | 'age' | 'email'
  Each iteration:   K = 'name'  → process T['name'] = string
                    K = 'age'   → process T['age']  = number
                    K = 'email' → process T['email'] = string
```

## Template Literal Types — String Manipulation at Type Level

```ts
type Greeting = `Hello, ${string}!`;  // any string matching that pattern
const g: Greeting = 'Hello, world!';  // ✓

type EventName = 'click' | 'focus' | 'blur';
type HandlerName = `on${Capitalize<EventName>}`;  // 'onClick' | 'onFocus' | 'onBlur'

// Combine with mapped types for dynamic property names:
type EventHandlers = {
  [K in EventName as `on${Capitalize<K>}`]: (e: Event) => void;
};
// { onClick: (e: Event) => void; onFocus: (e: Event) => void; onBlur: ... }
```

## `never` — The Bottom Type

`never` is the type with no possible values. It signals impossible states:

```ts
// Exhaustive checks — if TypeScript reaches this, all cases are handled:
function exhaustive(x: never): never {
  throw new Error(`Unhandled case: ${x}`);
}

type Shape = { kind: 'circle' } | { kind: 'square' };
function handle(s: Shape) {
  switch (s.kind) {
    case 'circle': return 'circle!';
    case 'square': return 'square!';
    default:       return exhaustive(s);  // ✓ s is never here — all cases handled
  }
  // If you add { kind: 'triangle' } to Shape,
  // the default branch becomes an error — triangle can't be passed as never
}
```

## Recursive Types

```ts
// JSON value — a type that refers to itself:
type JSONValue =
  | string
  | number
  | boolean
  | null
  | JSONValue[]           // array of JSONValues
  | { [key: string]: JSONValue }; // object of JSONValues

// Deep Partial — recursively makes all nested objects Partial too:
type DeepPartial<T> = T extends object
  ? { [K in keyof T]?: DeepPartial<T[K]> }
  : T;
```

## Advanced Type Cheatsheet

| Pattern | Syntax | Use case |
|---|---|---|
| Conditional | `T extends U ? A : B` | Branch on type |
| Distribution | conditional over union T | Filter union members |
| Infer | `infer U` inside extends | Capture sub-types |
| Mapped | `{ [K in keyof T]: ... }` | Transform all properties |
| Key remapping | `as NewKey` in mapped | Rename keys |
| Template literal | `` `prefix_${T}` `` | Construct string types |
| never | bottom type | Exhaustive checks, impossible states |

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting that conditional types distribute over unions — `Flatten<A | B>` applies to each member separately
- Using `infer` outside a conditional `extends` branch — invalid syntax
- Infinite recursion in recursive types — TypeScript has depth limits; add a base case
- `never[]` instead of typed array — calling a generic function with no args often infers `never`
- Mapped type modifiers: `+?` (add optional), `-?` (remove optional), `+readonly`, `-readonly` — forgetting the minus (-) to remove modifiers

## Connections
- **ts-utility-types** — all built-in utilities (Partial, Pick, Omit) are implemented as mapped/conditional types
- **ts-generics** — infer and conditional types heavily leverage generic type parameters
- **ts-interfaces-types** — discriminated unions feed into conditional type narrowing
- **ts-decorators** — metadata reflection uses conditional types for param/return extraction
